column51: I have been ordering from Scholastic Book Clubs for over 40 years.  I started ordering as a child then I started ordering as a teacher and parent.  I have always loved the great book selections and rewards that I have earned and/or ordered for my classroom and children.  Unfortunately, in the past few years I have been saddened by the topics/pictures that are in many of the books.  I am praying over whether I will continue to keep Scholastic as part of my classroom.  There is no guide in the small descriptions on the true content of the books/stories.  I have had to throw away a few books due to the content not matching my beliefs.

column51: It is extremely difficult to determine whether a book is the appropriate grade level for a child on this site.  Most parents don't know the reading level codes, and having to look at so many different types is time consuming and annoying.  The grade level ranges are also so large that it's hard to asses whether a book will be too hard or easy for a child.  If you could just provide more images of the pages and table of contents (if applicable), that would help immensely.  I often look for these books online to figure out which is appropriate, but I might as well buy it at that place rather than Scholastic.

column51: I really just wanted to log in and take care of funding my kids for the upcoming book fair. It is kind of frustrating that there isn't a link to the book fair stuff after you log into your class page.--like have a link somewhere obvious on the page back to the book fairs, etc. It would be more convenient if I could just log into my account and be able to easily access everything to do with Scholastic -- both ordering books and dealing with book fair. Also, both of my kids are listed on that book club page, and I would have preferred to have a way to set up the ewallet for them right there. I managed to do what I wanted, it just took longer than I expected because I had to open another tab with the main Scholastic page and search for our school's  book fair through that....and then had to go through the process twice to make two ewallets....would have liked to just set them up together. Maybe there's a way to do that, but it's not obvious. This site could be easier to navigate.

column51: I couldn’t find any books on Easter that were about God. Everything is about bunnies, which is cute, but there isn’t a very big or diverse selection. I’ve been to book fairs numerous times and I’m repeatedly disappointed with the types of books offered. Some were definitely not appropriate for kids even as thrillers containing things with girls that burst into flames when upset and learning to become witches, etc. The selection offered is honest terrible. I’ve shared this with several others and they were disappointed as well. We likely won’t be purchasing much more in the future.

column51: After placing two orders in the recently. I was notified that my daughter would receive a poster of Peppa the pig... she was excited to say the least and we weren't given any dimensions for the poster so i was basing it off the money spent $200+ so 24"x 36" for the poster to be. well the package showed up in mail today and the envelope was 12 x 18. I wanted to see my daughter's face when she pulled it out. So, all I did was cut the top open with letter opener Ever so slightly, so she can open it up. And she pulled out a piece of cardboard. Nothing else! The look in my daughter's eyes of defeat and sadness. Your company hurt my  Child not physically but Mentally and I can guarantee you that I will be informing the school About this situation and that we will no longer be participating in scholastics of any sort.  Especially after spending that amount of money for her happiness to be ripped away And believe me, it wasn't by choice. wallet doesn't work in book clubs for the schools.

column51: Scholastic has been a wonderful tool for getting my students to read, although, I have seen a drop in interest from most middle school and high school students purchasing from the flyers and website this school year. Maybe it's because of inflation on a national level, or as some students have mentioned, it's simply because they just don't see anything they like to read on the flyers. I wish the YA flyers were still available!! And, how can I get Scholastic coupons for my students who tend to buy books regularly? I can recall a few years ago receiving a booklet of coupons from Scholastic for my students that I did not have to pay for separately!
